  "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
  "body": "<!-- This form is for bug reports and feature requests ONLY! \r\n\r\nIf you're looking for help check [Stack Overflow](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/tagged/kubernetes) and the [troubleshooting guide](https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug-application-cluster/troubleshooting/).\r\n-->\r\n\r\n**Is this a BUG REPORT or FEATURE REQUEST?**:\r\n\r\n/kind bug\r\n\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\nFor IPv6, the node CIDR size is hard coded to /64. This causes an error bringing up the kube-controller, as the size must be for a smaller subnet (larger value) that what is used for the pod subnet, which is specified for some CNI plugins (e.g. Calico).\r\n\r\nIn addition, this is a catch-22, as the pod subnet prefix cannot be for a larger network (smaller value) than /66, so we cannot set it to /63, for example.\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\nThe node CIDR size should be computed, based on the pod subnet specified, so that it can meet the requirements. \r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\nBring up a cluster using KubeAdm, specifying IPv6 and choose any pod subnet prefix desired.\r\n\r\n**Anything else we need to know?**:\r\nNote, there is a second requirement, that the difference between pod subnet size and node CIDR size be 16 or less (issue 44918).\r\n\r\nI'll be submitting a proposed PR to address this.\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`): latest on master, using 1.9.2 in my case\r\n- Cloud provider or hardware configuration: bare metal, single node\r\n- OS (e.g. from /etc/os-release): Ubuntu 16.04\r\n- Kernel (e.g. `uname -a`):\r\nLinux bxb-c2-77 4.4.0-109-generic #132-Ubuntu SMP Tue Jan 9 19:52:39 UTC 2018 x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 GNU/Linux\r\n\r\n- Install tools: kubeadm\r\n- Others:\r\n/area ipv6\r\n/sig network\r\n",
